<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Independent clauses can stand alone as complete sentences, while dependent clauses (starting with subordinating conjunctions) and phrases cannot—test by reading aloud to see if you can stop talking at the end
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>There are exactly 5 ways to combine clauses correctly: (1) period between independent clauses, (2) comma + FANBOYS between independent clauses, (3) semicolon between independent clauses, (4) dependent + comma + independent, (5) independent + no comma + dependent
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>A comma by itself CANNOT join two independent clauses—this creates a comma splice which is always incorrect—fix using one of the 5 compound sentence rules
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>To solve sentence structure questions: (1) find the split point, (2) identify whether each side is independent, dependent, or a phrase, (3) apply the appropriate rule—look for punctuation variations in answer choices as clues
  </li>
</ul>

