<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The ACT tests exactly 4 comma types: (1) comma + FANBOYS joining independent clauses, (2) dependent clause before independent clause, (3) unnecessary information, and (4) listing items or adjectives
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use the "crossing-out" trick for unnecessary information commas—if you can remove the information and still have a complete sentence, it''s unnecessary and needs commas to separate it
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>"That" phrases never get commas while "which" phrases always get commas—for names, use commas only when the identifier is specific to one person (best friend, CEO) but not for general identifiers (friend, teacher)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Transitional words like "however" require specific punctuation: at the front with a comma after, in the middle between two commas, or between independent clauses with a semicolon before and comma after
  </li>
</ul>

