('3.2', 'math', 'Fractions', 'Fractions...', 'intermediate', 30, 12, '<!-- Topic 3.2: Fractions -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Fractions appear frequently on the ACT Math test, both as standalone problems and within larger algebra questions. This chapter covers ALL the fundamental techniques you need to answer any fraction question quickly and efficiently—from combining fractions with variables to using your calculator to convert between fractions and decimals.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Combining Fractions (Adding and Subtracting)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">To add or subtract fractions, you MUST have the same denominator:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You cannot add 1/2 + 2/5 directly—the denominators are different</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">First find the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">least common denominator</strong> (LCD)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then add or subtract the numerators while keeping the denominator the same</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick trick for finding the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">least common denominator</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Multiply the denominators together</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: For 1/2 + 2/5, LCD = 2 × 5 = 10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This always works, even if it''s not the smallest possible denominator</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">On the ACT, any common denominator is fine—you don''t need the smallest one</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Step-by-step process for combining fractions:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 1/2 + 2/5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Find LCD = 2 × 5 = 10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Convert each fraction: 1/2 = 5/10, and 2/5 = 4/10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Add numerators: 5/10 + 4/10 = 9/10</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Fractions with variables in denominators (harder but same concept):</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 1/x + 3/(x-4)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">LCD = x(x-4) [multiply the denominators]</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply first fraction by (x-4)/(x-4): (x-4)/[x(x-4)]</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply second fraction by x/x: 3x/[x(x-4)]</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Add: (x-4+3x)/[x(x-4)] = (4x-4)/[x(x-4)]</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Dividing Fractions ("Keep, Flip, Change")
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong>"Keep, Flip, Change"</strong> method for dividing fractions:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Keep</strong> the first fraction exactly as it is</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Flip</strong> the second fraction (take the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reciprocal</strong>)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Change</strong> the division sign to multiplication</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (2/3) ÷ (4/5) = (2/3) × (5/4) = 10/12 = 5/6</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">This works even when dividing a fraction by a whole number:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (2/3) ÷ 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Write 3 as 3/1, then flip to get 1/3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Result: (2/3) × (1/3) = 2/9</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">reciprocal</strong> of a fraction:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Flip the numerator and denominator</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Reciprocal of 3/4 is 4/3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Reciprocal of 5 is 1/5 (since 5 = 5/1)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Reciprocal of x/(x-2) is (x-2)/x</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Why "keep, flip, change" works:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Dividing by a number is the same as multiplying by its reciprocal</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 10 ÷ 2 = 10 × (1/2) = 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same principle applies to fractions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Simplifying Fractions (Critical Rules!)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Rule: You can ONLY simplify if you can divide ALL terms by the same number</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (2x+10)/4 CAN be simplified (divide all by 2) → (x+5)/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (8x+3)/4 CANNOT be simplified (can''t divide 3 by 4)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Common mistake: (2x+10)/4 ≠ (x+10)/2 ❌ (You MUST divide ALL terms!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When you CANNOT simplify, split the fraction instead:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (8x+3)/4 = 8x/4 + 3/4 = 2x + 3/4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You CAN split numerators: (a+b)/c = a/c + b/c ✓</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You CANNOT split denominators: a/(b+c) ≠ a/b + a/c ❌</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Simplifying with variables in the denominator:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 3/(6x+30) CAN be simplified → 3/[3(2x+10)] → 1/(2x+10)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 3/(6x+10) CANNOT be simplified (can''t divide 10 by 3)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same rule: ALL terms must be divisible by the same number</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">CRITICAL: You cannot split denominators!
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">3/(6x+10) ≠ 3/6x + 3/10 ❌ WRONG!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is one of the most common mistakes students make</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When in doubt, leave the denominator together</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Getting Rid of Fractions (Multiply by LCD)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">For equations with only numbers in denominators, eliminate fractions:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Find the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">least common multiple</strong> (LCM) of all denominators</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply EVERY term by the LCM</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">All fractions will disappear, leaving only whole numbers</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then solve the equation normally</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: (1/4)x + (1/2) = (3/8)x
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">LCM of 4, 2, and 8 is 8</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply all terms by 8: (1/4)x×8 + (1/2)×8 = (3/8)x×8</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Simplify: 2x + 4 = 3x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: x = 4</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">More complex example with subtraction:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (3x/5) - (2x/6) - (1/2) = (x/10)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">LCM of 5, 6, 2, and 10 is 30</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply all terms by 30: 18x - 10x - 15 = 3x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Simplify: 8x - 15 = 3x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: 5x = 15, so x = 3</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When to use this method:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you struggle with fractions, ALWAYS use this method!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">It turns difficult fraction problems into easy whole number problems</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Works great when ALL denominators are numbers (not variables)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Calculator Strategies for Fractions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Strategy #1: Turn fractions into decimals</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (3/4)x - (2/5) = (1/2)x becomes 0.75x - 0.4 = 0.5x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: 0.75x = 0.5x + 0.4 → 0.25x = 0.4 → x = 1.6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then convert 1.6 back to a fraction if needed, or check answer choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This avoids dealing with fractions entirely!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Strategy #2: Convert decimals to fractions using your calculator</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>TI-83/84:</strong> Enter decimal → Press MATH → Select "Frac" → Press ENTER</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>TI-30XS:</strong> Enter decimal → Press 2nd → Press PRB → Select F◂▸D → Press ENTER</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you have a different calculator, YouTube has tutorials for your model</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Strategy #3: Use parentheses properly!</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS put the entire numerator in parentheses</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS put the entire denominator in parentheses</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: To enter (2x+1)/(x-3), type: (2x+1)÷(x-3)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Without parentheses, calculator follows order of operations incorrectly</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Strategy #4: Compare answer choices as decimals</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you solved to get x = 1.6 (decimal)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">And answer choices are fractions like 8/5, 5/3, 13/10, etc.</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Enter each fraction in calculator to see which equals 1.6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">8/5 = 1.6 ✓ That''s your answer!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Strategy #5: Backsolving</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the question asks "what is the value of x?" with answer choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Plug each answer choice back into the original equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use your calculator to check which one makes the equation true</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is often faster than solving algebraically!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
6. Test-Taking Tips for Fractions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use your calculator strategically</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For numerical fractions: let calculator do the work</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For algebraic fractions: write out steps carefully</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Save mental energy for the hard problems</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use substitution for "equivalent" questions</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If asked "which expression is equivalent," plug in a test value</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: If the original has x, try x = 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Calculate both expressions—they should give the same answer</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is often faster than algebraic manipulation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Remember the "cannot split denominators" rule</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">a/(b+c) ≠ a/b + a/c ❌ This is ALWAYS wrong!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">But (a+b)/c = a/c + b/c ✓ Splitting numerators is OK</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This mistake appears in wrong answer choices frequently</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>When in doubt, eliminate fractions</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If all denominators are numbers, multiply by LCM</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If dealing with fractions makes you nervous, turn them into decimals</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Both methods turn hard problems into easy ones</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Master "Keep, Flip, Change" for division</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This simple rule handles ALL fraction division</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Keep first, flip second, change to multiplication</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Works every time, no exceptions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>To combine fractions, multiply denominators to find LCD, convert all fractions, then add/subtract numerators—works for both numbers and variables
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>You can ONLY simplify if you can divide ALL terms by the same number; you CAN split numerators (a+b)/c = a/c + b/c but you CANNOT split denominators
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>To eliminate fractions from equations, multiply all terms by the LCM—this turns fraction problems into whole number problems
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use your calculator to convert between fractions and decimals, backsolve with answer choices, and always use parentheses around numerators and denominators
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('3.6', 'math', 'Absolute Value', 'Absolute Value...', 'intermediate', 30, 12, '<div style="max-width: 55rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 1rem 1.5rem;">

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. What is Absolute Value? (Definition and Basic Operations)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Definition: Absolute value is the distance from zero on a number line</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Distance is always positive, so absolute value is always positive or zero</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|3| = 3 (3 is three units from zero)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|-3| = 3 (-3 is also three units from zero)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Order of Operations with Absolute Value:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Complete all math INSIDE the absolute value bars first</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Take the absolute value (make positive)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Complete remaining operations outside the bars</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Example: |3 - 7| + 2</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Work inside bars: |3 - 7| = |-4|</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Take absolute value: |-4| = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Complete outside: 4 + 2 = 6</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Calculator Tip:</strong> Most calculators have an "abs(" function for absolute value
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">On TI calculators: MATH → NUM → abs(</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You can use this to check your work quickly</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Solving Absolute Value Equations with Variables
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Key Concept: Absolute value equations with variables have TWO solutions</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Why? Because both a positive and negative number can have the same absolute value</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: |x - 3| = 5 means (x - 3) could equal 5 OR -5</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Four-Step Process to Solve:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Add/subtract any constants OUTSIDE the absolute value bars to move them to the other side</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Multiply/divide any coefficients directly IN FRONT of the absolute value bars</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Set the expression inside equal to BOTH the positive and negative value</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 4:</strong> Solve both equations to get both solutions</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Example: 3|2x + 1| - 6 = 45</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Add 6 to both sides → 3|2x + 1| = 51</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Divide by 3 → |2x + 1| = 17</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Set up two equations:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• 2x + 1 = 17 → 2x = 16 → x = 8</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• 2x + 1 = -17 → 2x = -18 → x = -9</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solution set: {-9, 8}</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Common Mistake:</strong> Only finding one solution
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS check answer choices - if they show two values, you need both solutions!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you only find one solution, you probably forgot the negative case</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Absolute Value Inequalities (The Most Difficult Type)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Key Concept: Absolute value inequalities have INTERVAL solutions (not just two numbers)</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|x| < 3 means "all numbers less than 3 units from zero"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solution: -3 < x < 3 (between -3 and 3)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Two Main Types:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Type 1: |x| < a or |x| ≤ a</strong> (Less than)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Solution format: -a < x < a (or -a ≤ x ≤ a)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• One compound inequality</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Think: "close to zero" or "between two values"</li>

      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; margin-top: 0.5rem;"><strong>Type 2: |x| > a or |x| ≥ a</strong> (Greater than)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Solution format: x < -a AND x > a (or x ≤ -a AND x ≥ a)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Two separate inequalities with "AND"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Think: "far from zero" or "outside the interval"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Four-Step Process:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Isolate the absolute value bars (move all terms outside to the other side)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Determine the type (< means "between", > means "outside")</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Set up the inequality based on type</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Step 4:</strong> Solve for the variable</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Example 1: |x + 3| - 4 < 1</strong> (Less than type)
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Add 4 to both sides → |x + 3| < 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: This is "less than" type, so solution is between -5 and 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Set up: -5 < x + 3 < 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Subtract 3 from all parts: -8 < x < 2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Example 2: |½x + 2| > 3</strong> (Greater than type)
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Already isolated</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: This is "greater than" type, so solution is outside -3 and 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Set up two inequalities:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• ½x + 2 < -3 → ½x < -5 → x < -10</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• ½x + 2 > 3 → ½x > 1 → x > 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Solution: x < -10 AND x > 2</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Advanced Absolute Value Concepts
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Absolute Value Properties You Must Know:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>If |a| = -a, then a ≤ 0</strong> (a must be zero or negative)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Why? The only way absolute value equals its negative is if the number is ≤ 0</li>

      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; margin-top: 0.5rem;"><strong>For x > 0 and y < 0: |x| - |y| = x - (-y) = x + y</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Positive number''s absolute value = itself</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Negative number''s absolute value = its opposite</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Comparing Absolute Values:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If a < b < c and c > 0:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• |c| is always the largest (furthest from zero on positive side)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• Can''t determine which of |a| or |b| is larger without more info</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: If a = -10, b = -2, c = 5:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• |a| = 10, |b| = 2, |c| = 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0; padding-left: 1rem;">• |a| > |c| even though a < c</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Distance Interpretation:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>|x - a| = d</strong> means "x is d units away from a"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: |x + 2| = 8 means "x is 8 units from -2"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Note: x + 2 = x - (-2), so we''re measuring distance from -2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solutions: x = 6 or x = -10 (both are 8 units from -2)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Equivalent Expressions:</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|x - y - z| = |x - (y + z)|</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This also equals |-x + y + z| (opposite signs for all terms)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Absolute value of opposites are equal: |a| = |-a|</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Special Case: No Solution</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you end up with something like |-3x + 1| + 15 < 12:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Isolate: |-3x + 1| < -3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Absolute value can NEVER be negative, so NO SOLUTION!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Absolute Value
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Tip #1: Look at answer choices first to determine what type of problem it is</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Two numbers in braces like {-9, 8}? → Absolute value equation (2 solutions)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Compound inequality like -8 < x < 2? → Absolute value inequality (interval)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Two inequalities with AND? → Greater than type inequality</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Tip #2: For equations, backsolve by plugging in answer choices</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the question asks for the solution to |2x - 4| = 10:</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Try x = 7: |2(7) - 4| = |14 - 4| = |10| = 10 ✓</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is often faster than algebraic solving</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Tip #3: Remember the critical patterns</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|x| < a → between two values (one compound inequality)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">|x| > a → outside two values (two separate inequalities with AND)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Memorize these patterns - they appear on EVERY ACT test!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Tip #4: Watch out for the "no solution" trap</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you isolate absolute value bars and get |something| < negative number → NO SOLUTION</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you isolate and get |something| = negative number → NO SOLUTION</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This often appears as answer choice "No solution" or "The empty set"</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<div style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #667eea 0%, #764ba2 100%); padding: 1.75rem; border-radius: 0.75rem; margin: 3rem 0 2rem 0; box-shadow: 0 10px 25px -5px rgba(0,0,0,0.2);">
  <div style="color: white; font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 1rem; text-align: center; letter-spacing: 0.5px;">
    ✨ Key Takeaways
  </div>
  <ul style="color: white; margin: 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.9; font-size: 0.98rem;">
    <li style="margin: 0.5rem 0;"><strong>Absolute value equations with variables ALWAYS have two solutions</strong> - set the inside equal to both positive and negative values</li>
    <li style="margin: 0.5rem 0;"><strong>For inequalities: |x| < a means -a < x < a (between), while |x| > a means x < -a AND x > a (outside)</strong></li>
    <li style="margin: 0.5rem 0;"><strong>Always isolate the absolute value bars first</strong> before setting up your equations or inequalities</li>
    <li style="margin: 0.5rem 0;"><strong>Remember: absolute value can never be negative</strong> - if you get |something| < 0, the answer is "no solution"</li>
  </ul>
</div>

</div>')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('3.3', 'math', 'Exponents and Roots', 'Exponents and Roots...', 'intermediate', 30, 13, '<!-- Topic 3.3: Exponents and Roots -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.0 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Exponents and roots appear frequently on the ACT Math test, testing your ability to apply <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponent rules</strong> and simplify <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">radicals</strong>. Mastering the seven exponent rules and understanding how to factor numbers under radicals will help you solve these problems quickly and accurately.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Exponent Rules (Memorize These!)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The seven essential <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">exponent rules</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Product Rule: a^x × a^y = a^(x+y)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 3³ × 3⁴ = 3⁷</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When multiplying with the same base, add the exponents</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Quotient Rule: a^x ÷ a^y = a^(x-y)</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 5⁷ ÷ 5² = 5⁵</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When dividing with the same base, subtract the exponents</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Power Rule: (a^x)^y = a^(xy)</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (2³)² = 2⁶</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When raising a power to a power, multiply the exponents</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">CRITICAL: Distribute to ALL terms, including coefficients!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (-2xy³)² = 4x²y⁶ (the -2 becomes 4!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Negative Exponent Rule: a^(-x) = 1/a^x</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 2^(-3) = 1/2³ = 1/8</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Negative exponents mean "reciprocal"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Trick: Moving a term from numerator to denominator (or vice versa) flips the sign of the exponent</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: x^(-2)/y^(-3) = y³/x²</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Zero Power Rule: a^0 = 1</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 139⁰ = 1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ANY number to the zero power equals 1 (except 0⁰ which is undefined)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>One Power Rule: a^1 = a</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (-4)¹ = -4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Any number to the first power is itself</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Fraction Power Rule</strong>: a^(x/y) = ʸ√(a^x)
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 8^(2/3) = ³√(8²) = ³√64 = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Or: 8^(2/3) = (³√8)² = 2² = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The denominator is the root, the numerator is the power</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Solving Exponential Equations
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When bases are the same, set exponents equal:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If 4^(3x+1) = 4^(-x+7), then 3x+1 = -x+7</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Solve: 4x = 6, so x = 3/2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This works because equal exponential expressions with the same base must have equal exponents</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When bases are different, make them the same:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 9^(2x) = 27^(x+4)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Recognize that 9 = 3² and 27 = 3³</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Rewrite: (3²)^(2x) = (3³)^(x+4)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Simplify: 3^(4x) = 3^(3x+12)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Set exponents equal: 4x = 3x+12, so x = 12</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Calculator method - Backsolving:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the question gives answer choices, plug them in!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Calculate both sides of the equation with each answer choice</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The correct answer will make both sides equal</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is often faster than algebraic manipulation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Simplifying Radicals
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">To simplify a square root, factor and take out pairs:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: √50 = √(5×5×2) = 5√2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">There''s a pair of 5''s, so take the 5 out front</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The 2 is not part of a pair, so it stays under the radical</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">More complex example:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">√108 = √(2×2×3×3×3) = (2×3)√3 = 6√3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">We have a pair of 2''s and a pair of 3''s, so take both out</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The third 3 is not part of a pair, so it stays under the radical</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Going backwards - putting numbers back under the radical:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Take the number outside and square it under the radical</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 6√3 = √(6×6×3) = √108</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is useful when you need to combine radicals</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Combining radicals (only like radicals can be combined):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: √45 + √20 = 3√5 + 2√5 = 5√5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">First simplify each radical: √45 = √(3×3×5) = 3√5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">And: √20 = √(2×2×5) = 2√5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then combine like radicals by adding coefficients</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Operations with Radicals
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Multiplying and dividing radicals:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>√x × √y = √(xy)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: √8 × √2 = √16 = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>√x ÷ √y = √(x/y)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: √50 ÷ √2 = √(50/2) = √25 = 5</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Solving radical equations:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: If √(2x) = 5√6, solve for x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Method #1: Move the 5 under the radical: √(2x) = √(6×5×5) = √150</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Since the radicals are equal, the contents must be equal: 2x = 150, so x = 75</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Alternate method - square both sides:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">(√(2x))² = (5√6)²</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2x = 25 × 6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2x = 150, so x = 75</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Cube roots and higher roots follow the same rules:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">³√(xy) = ³√x × ³√y</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: ³√16 = ³√(8×2) = ³√8 × ³√2 = 2³√2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">For cube roots, take out groups of three instead of pairs</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Test-Taking Tips for Exponents and Roots
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Memorize all seven exponent rules COLD</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You cannot skip any of them—all appear on the ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Practice until you can apply them instantly without thinking</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The product, quotient, and power rules are tested most often</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>When distributing powers, distribute to EVERYTHING</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t forget coefficients! (-2x)³ = -8x³, not -2x³</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t forget ALL variables! (3xy²)² = 9x²y⁴, not 9xy⁴</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the #1 mistake students make with exponents</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Use your calculator to backsolve when possible</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If the question gives answer choices, plugging in is often faster</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Calculate both sides of the equation with each answer</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This works great for exponential equations and radical equations</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>For radicals, factor methodically</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Break numbers down into prime factors to find all pairs</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 72 = 2×2×2×3×3 → pairs of 2''s and 3''s → 6√2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Don''t rush—missing a pair means getting the wrong answer</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong>Look for common bases in exponential equations</strong>
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Recognize that 4 = 2², 8 = 2³, 16 = 2⁴</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Recognize that 9 = 3², 27 = 3³, 81 = 3⁴</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Converting to the same base makes equations much easier to solve</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Master all seven exponent rules, especially product (a^x × a^y = a^(x+y)), quotient (a^x ÷ a^y = a^(x-y)), and power ((a^x)^y = a^(xy))—these are tested most frequently
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When distributing powers, apply to ALL terms including coefficients: (-2xy³)² = 4x²y⁶, not -2x²y⁶
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Simplify radicals by factoring and taking out pairs: √108 = √(2×2×3×3×3) = 6√3
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Use backsolving with your calculator when answer choices are given—often faster than algebraic manipulation for exponential and radical equations
  </li>
</ul>
')
