INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('6.1', 'math', 'Mean, Median, and Mode', 'Mean, Median, and Mode...', 'intermediate', 30, 26, '<!-- Topic 6.1: Mean, Median, Mode, and Range -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.2 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Mean, median, mode, and range are fundamental statistical measures. The ACT most frequently tests the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mean</strong> (average), requiring you to find missing values or combine averages from different groups.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Basic Definitions
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Four statistical measures you must know:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Mean (average):</strong> The sum divided by the number of items</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Median:</strong> The middle number when ordered from smallest to largest</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Mode:</strong> The number that appears most often</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Range:</strong> The difference between the largest and smallest numbers</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The fundamental average formula:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Average = Sum ÷ Number of Items</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Rearrange to: <strong>Sum = Average × Number of Items</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This rearranged form is crucial for many ACT questions!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Memorize both forms</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Find the mean of {2, 5, 8, 9}
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sum = 2 + 5 + 8 + 9 = 24</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Number of items = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Mean = 24 ÷ 4 = 6</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Finding Missing Values Using Mean
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The most common ACT question type:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You''re given the average and most values</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Asked to find a missing value</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use algebra to solve</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Five students averaged 24 points. Four scored 22, 28, 17, and 25. Find the fifth score.
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Set up the equation</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Let x = fifth student''s score</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">24 = (22 + 28 + 17 + 25 + x) ÷ 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Simplify</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">24 = (92 + x) ÷ 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Multiply both sides by 5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">120 = 92 + x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 4: Solve for x</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">x = 28</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">CRITICAL shortcut:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Always multiply average by number of items first</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This gives you the total sum immediately</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Makes solving much easier!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">In example above: 24 × 5 = 120 (total sum)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Combining Averages
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">CRITICAL: You CANNOT just average the averages!
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">When combining groups with different sizes</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Must find total sum for ALL items</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then divide by total number of items</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Period 1 has 6 students averaging 85. Period 2 has 9 students averaging 90. Find combined average.
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Find total points for Period 1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sum = Average × Number</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sum₁ = 85 × 6 = 510 points</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Find total points for Period 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Sum₂ = 90 × 9 = 810 points</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Calculate combined average</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Combined Average = (510 + 810) ÷ (6 + 9)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Combined Average = 1320 ÷ 15 = 88</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common mistake to avoid:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">WRONG: (85 + 90) ÷ 2 = 87.5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This ignores that groups have different sizes</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Period 2 has MORE students, so its average should count more</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Always convert to total sums first!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Working with Median
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">median</strong> is positional:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Depends on WHERE values fall in ordered list</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">NOT the numerical values themselves</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS order the data first!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding median with odd number of values:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: {4, 1, 9, 3, 7}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Order: {1, 3, 4, 7, 9}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Pick middle value: 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Median = 4</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding median with even number of values:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: {2, 8, 5, 9, 3, 6}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: Order: {2, 3, 5, 6, 8, 9}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Find two middle values: 5 and 6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Average them: (5 + 6) ÷ 2 = 5.5</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Median = 5.5</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding missing value when median is given:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: Median of {3, 7, x, 12} is 8. Find x.</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 1: With 4 values, median = average of 2nd and 3rd</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 2: Order known values: {3, ?, ?, 12}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Step 3: Test where x fits</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If x ≥ 7, order is {3, 7, x, 12}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Median = (7 + x) ÷ 2 = 8</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">7 + x = 16 → x = 9 ✓</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Mode and Range
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">mode</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Count how many times each value appears</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Mode = value(s) with highest frequency</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: {3, 5, 5, 7, 7, 7, 9} → Mode = 7 (appears 3 times)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Can have multiple modes if values tie for most frequent</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">No mode if all values appear equally</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">range</strong>:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Range = Maximum - Minimum</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: {12, 4, 18, 7, 9}</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Max = 18, Min = 4</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Range = 18 - 4 = 14</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">How adding values affects statistics:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Adding value equal to current mean → mean stays same</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Adding value larger than max → range increases</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Adding value smaller than min → range increases</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Adding value between min and max → range stays same</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>The fundamental formula: Average = Sum ÷ Number of Items (rearrange to: Sum = Average × Number)
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>When combining averages, find each group''s total sum first (Sum = Average × Count), add sums, then divide by total count—NEVER just average the averages!
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>For median, ALWAYS order data first: odd count = pick middle value; even count = average two middle values
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Mode = most frequent value; Range = Max - Min
  </li>
</ul>
')
ON CONFLICT (id) DO UPDATE SET
  section = EXCLUDED.section,
  title = EXCLUDED.title,
  description = EXCLUDED.description,
  content = EXCLUDED.content,
  estimated_minutes = EXCLUDED.estimated_minutes,
  order_index = EXCLUDED.order_index;

INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('6.2', 'math', 'Advanced Statistics', 'Advanced Statistics...', 'intermediate', 30, 27, '<!-- Topic 6.2: Probability -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.2 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Probability measures the likelihood of an event occurring. The ACT tests basic probability calculations, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">independent events</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">dependent events</strong> (with and without replacement).
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Basic Probability Formula
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The fundamental probability formula:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Probability = Desired Outcomes ÷ Total Possible Outcomes</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Always expressed as a fraction, decimal, or percentage</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability values range from 0 (impossible) to 1 (certain)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: A bag contains 38 candies: 18 blue, 10 red, 5 yellow, 3 green, 2 pink
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What is the probability of selecting a yellow candy?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Desired outcomes = 5 (yellow candies)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total outcomes = 38 (total candies)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability = 5/38</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Finding probability of NOT selecting something:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Count everything that ISN''T the unwanted outcome</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: Probability of NOT selecting blue candy</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Blue candies = 18, so NOT blue = 38 - 18 = 20</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability = 20/38 = 10/19</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Multiple Events (AND Rule)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">CRITICAL: When events happen in sequence, MULTIPLY their probabilities
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The word "and" means multiply</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(A and B) = P(A) × P(B)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>Common mistake:</strong> Adding probabilities instead of multiplying</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Select a red candy AND THEN a green candy
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">First selection: P(red) = 10/38</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Second selection: P(green) = 3/37 (only 37 left after first pick)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(red AND green) = (10/38) × (3/37) = 30/1406 = 15/703</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Without replacement vs. with replacement:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Without replacement:</strong> Total decreases after each selection</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">After picking first candy, only 37 remain (as shown above)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">With replacement:</strong> Total stays the same (item returned)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If candy is replaced: P(red AND green) = (10/38) × (3/38)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Multiple Possibilities (OR Rule)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When you want probability of one event OR another event:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The word "or" means add</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This applies when events are mutually exclusive (can''t both happen)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Probability of selecting red OR yellow candy
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(red) = 10/38</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(yellow) = 5/38</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(red OR yellow) = 10/38 + 5/38 = 15/38</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick method when events don''t overlap:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Count total desired outcomes directly</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Red or yellow = 10 + 5 = 15 candies total</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability = 15/38 (same result, faster!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Probability with Geometric Scenarios
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Some ACT probability questions use area or length:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability = Desired Area ÷ Total Area</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Or: Probability = Desired Length ÷ Total Length</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same concept as basic probability, just with geometric measurements</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Dartboard with target circle inside square board
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Square board: 10 inches × 10 inches = 100 square inches</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Target circle: radius 3 inches, area = π(3)² = 9π square inches</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability of hitting target = 9π/100</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Random point on a line segment
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Line segment from 0 to 20</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">What''s probability the point is between 5 and 12?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Desired length = 12 - 5 = 7</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total length = 20</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Probability = 7/20</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. Common Probability Scenarios on the ACT
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Selecting from a group:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Marbles in a bag</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Cards from a deck</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Students in a class</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Count favorable outcomes and divide by total</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Multiple selections:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ALWAYS check: with or without replacement?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Without replacement is more common on ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Remember to decrease the total for each subsequent pick</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">At least one success:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Often easier to find probability of NO successes first</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Then: P(at least one) = 1 - P(none)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: P(at least one red) = 1 - P(no reds selected)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Complementary events:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">P(event) + P(NOT event) = 1</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If P(rain) = 0.3, then P(no rain) = 0.7</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Use this when "NOT" probability is easier to calculate</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Basic probability = Desired Outcomes ÷ Total Outcomes; probability of NOT occurring = count everything that isn''t the unwanted outcome
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Multiple events use AND rule (multiply probabilities); remember to adjust totals for "without replacement" scenarios
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Multiple possibilities use OR rule (add probabilities); for mutually exclusive events, you can count desired outcomes directly
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Geometric probability uses area or length ratios; complementary events: P(event) + P(NOT event) = 1
  </li>
</ul>
')
