INSERT INTO lessons (id, section, title, description, difficulty, estimated_minutes, order_index, content) VALUES
('6.3', 'math', 'Probability', 'Probability...', 'intermediate', 30, 28, '<!-- Topic 6.3: Counting, Permutations, and Combinations -->
<!-- Restructured using Golden Template v5.2 -->

<p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0;">
Counting problems ask "how many" ways something can occur. The ACT tests <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">factorials</strong>, the <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fundamental counting principle</strong>, <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">permutations</strong>, and <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">combinations</strong>.
</p>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
1. Factorials
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">factorial</strong> function, symbolized by "!", multiplies an integer by every integer below it:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>n! = n × (n-1) × (n-2) × ... × 2 × 1</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 5! = 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 3! = 3 × 2 × 1 = 6</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Special case: 0! = 1 (by definition)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Most ACT factorial questions are simple calculations:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: 2! + 4! = ?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2! = 2 × 1 = 2</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">4! = 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 24</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2! + 4! = 2 + 24 = 26</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Calculator tip:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Most calculators have a "!" button</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Check your calculator manual if unsure</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Saves time on larger factorials like 7! or 10!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Simplifying factorial fractions (advanced):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: (3! × n!)/(n+1)!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Expand: (6 × n × (n-1) × ... × 1)/((n+1) × n × (n-1) × ... × 1)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Cancel common terms: n! cancels out</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Result: 6/(n+1)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
2. Fundamental Counting Principle
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The <strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">fundamental counting principle</strong>: If one event can occur in m ways and another can occur in n ways, then both can occur in m × n ways
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Multiply the number of choices for each decision</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the MOST common counting method on the ACT</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Works when order matters AND when order doesn''t matter (for independent choices)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Creating outfits
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">You have 3 shirts, 4 pairs of shoes, and 5 pairs of pants</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">How many different outfits can you create?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total outfits = 3 × 4 × 5 = 60</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: Lock codes
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">A lock code has 3 numbers (0-9) and 2 letters (A-Z)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">How many different codes are possible?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Numbers: 10 choices for each digit = 10 × 10 × 10 = 1,000</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Letters: 26 choices for each letter = 26 × 26 = 676</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total codes = 1,000 × 676 = 676,000</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">When choices decrease (without replacement):
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: Selecting 3 people from a group of 10 for 1st, 2nd, 3rd place</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1st place: 10 choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2nd place: 9 choices (one person already selected)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">3rd place: 8 choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total arrangements = 10 × 9 × 8 = 720</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
3. Permutations (Order Matters)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Permutations</strong> count arrangements where ORDER MATTERS:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Different orderings count as different outcomes</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: ABC is different from BAC</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Used for rankings, positions, seating arrangements</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The permutation formula:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>nPr = n!/(n-r)!</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">n = total number of items</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r = number of items being selected</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">nPr = number of ways to arrange r items from n items</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: How many ways can you arrange 3 books from a shelf of 5 books?
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">n = 5 books total, r = 3 books selected</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5P3 = 5!/(5-3)! = 5!/2!</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5P3 = (5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1)/(2 × 1)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5P3 = 120/2 = 60 arrangements</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Shortcut using fundamental counting principle:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same problem: 5 books, select 3</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">1st position: 5 choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">2nd position: 4 choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">3rd position: 3 choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Total = 5 × 4 × 3 = 60 (same answer, faster!)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
4. Combinations (Order Doesn''t Matter)
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;"><strong style="color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600; text-decoration: underline;">Combinations</strong> count selections where ORDER DOESN''T MATTER:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Different orderings count as the SAME outcome</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Example: ABC is the same as BAC is the same as CAB</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Used for groups, committees, selections</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">The combination formula:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;"><strong>nCr = n!/(r!(n-r)!)</strong></li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">n = total number of items</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">r = number of items being selected</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">nCr = number of ways to select r items from n items</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Example: How many ways can you select 3 books from a shelf of 5 books?
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">n = 5 books, r = 3 books (order doesn''t matter)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5C3 = 5!/(3! × 2!)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5C3 = (5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1)/((3 × 2 × 1) × (2 × 1))</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">5C3 = 120/(6 × 2) = 120/12 = 10</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Key difference from permutations:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Same problem with permutations gave 60 arrangements</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">With combinations, we get 10 selections</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Combinations are ALWAYS smaller (or equal) to permutations</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">We divide by r! to remove duplicate orderings</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="margin-top: 5rem; margin-bottom: 0.75rem; font-weight: 700;">
5. When to Use Each Method
</h3>

<ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 1rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem; line-height: 1.7;">
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use <strong>Fundamental Counting Principle</strong> when:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Making multiple independent choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Creating combinations of items (outfits, meals, codes)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">This is the FASTEST method—use it whenever possible!</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use <strong>Permutations</strong> when:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ORDER MATTERS in the selection</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Words: "arrange," "order," "rank," "position"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Examples: Race finish order, seating arrangements, passwords</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Use <strong>Combinations</strong> when:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">ORDER DOESN''T MATTER in the selection</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Words: "group," "committee," "team," "select," "choose"</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Examples: Choosing committee members, selecting toppings, forming groups</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Quick decision tree:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Question asks "how many outfits/meals/codes?" → Fundamental Counting Principle (multiply choices)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Question asks "arrange" or "order" → Permutation (order matters)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Question asks "select" or "choose a group" → Combination (order doesn''t matter)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li style="margin: 0.3rem 0;">Common ACT trick:
    <ul style="margin: 0.3rem 0; padding-left: 1.5rem;">
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">The ACT will often make permutation and combination both answer choices</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">Read carefully: does order matter?</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you select people for a "committee," order doesn''t matter (combination)</li>
      <li style="margin: 0.2rem 0;">If you select people for "president, VP, secretary," order matters (permutation)</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<h3 style="visibility: hidden; margin: 0; padding: 0; line-height: 0; height: 0;">
Hidden Separator
</h3>

<h3 style="color: #2e7d32; font-size: 1.4rem; font-weight: 700; margin: 3rem 0 1.5rem 0;">
Key Takeaways
</h3>

<ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0;">
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Factorials: n! = n × (n-1) × ... × 1; most calculators have a "!" button for quick calculation
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Fundamental Counting Principle (MOST COMMON): multiply the number of choices for each decision—use whenever possible!
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Permutations (order matters): nPr = n!/(n-r)!; use for "arrange," "order," "rank," "position" questions
  </li>
  <li style="margin-bottom: 0.8rem; color: #2e7d32; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6;">
    <span style="color: #4caf50; font-weight: bold; margin-right: 0.5rem;">✓</span>Combinations (order doesn''t matter): nCr = n!/(r!(n-r)!); use for "select," "choose," "group," "committee" questions
  </li>
</ul>
')
